# TypeScript, React, Next.js standards

## TypeScript

- `strict` mode; never use `any` — prefer `unknown` and narrow with type guards
- `interface` for object shapes; `type` for unions and utilities
- Explicit return types on exported functions and Server Actions
- Validate external input at boundaries with Zod (forms, params, Supabase rows)
- Use generated Supabase types (`Database` from `supabase gen types`)
- `satisfies` for config objects; discriminated unions for UI/state variants

## React

- Functional components only; follow Rules of Hooks
- Prefer composition; avoid unnecessary prop drilling
- Minimize `useEffect` — prefer derived state, Server Components, or event handlers
- Stable `key` props on lists; never use array index when order can change
- Forms: `react-hook-form` + Zod resolver + shadcn/ui form primitives
- Accessible markup: semantic HTML, labels, focus management

## Next.js (App Router)

- **Server Components by default** — `"use client"` only for interactivity, browser APIs, or hooks
- Fetch data in Server Components; pass serializable props to Client Components
- Mutations via **Server Actions** with `revalidatePath` / `revalidateTag`
- Supabase: `@supabase/ssr` — server client in RSC/Actions, browser client in Client Components only
- Auth in `middleware.ts`; protect routes by role before page render
- Colocate `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx`, and Suspense per route segment
- Use `next/link` and `next/image`
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` only for browser-safe env vars; service role key server-only
- Route Handlers only when Server Actions are insufficient

## Code quality

- Match existing project patterns before new abstractions
- Small, focused components; co-locate route UI under `src/app/`
- Fix ESLint errors before finishing a task
